visioned for both courses and research topics in domestic violence, family violence, gender and law, and sociology of law, the book challenges readers to understand intimate partner violence not solely, or even primarily, as a criminal law concern but as an economic, public health, community, and human rights problem. It also argues that only by viewing intimate partner violence through these lenses can we develop a balanced policy agenda for addressing it. At a moment when we are examining our national addiction to punishment, Decriminalizing Domestic Violence offers a thoughtful, pragmatic roadmap to real reform.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aFamily violencezUnited StatesxPrevention. 0aIntimate partner violencezUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh  aabuse.  abalanced policy agenda.  abroken system.  acriminal justice reform.  acriminal law.  acriminal legal system.  adomestic violence.  afamily violence.  afinancial resources.  agender.  alaw.  alegal resources.  amoral responsibility.  anational addiction to punishment.  apartner violence.  aresearch.  asocial resources.  asociology of law.  ateaching.  aunited states.  aviolence.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106676770 cprintz978052029556840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096829540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520968295423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520968295/original  a978-3-11-066767-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-073776-9  DTL Humanities 2020b2020  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles